<div class="page">
  <header class="hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">React on Rails Pro &middot; RSC Flagship Demo</p>
    <h1>Slow Section (Late Suspense Boundary)</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      The header you are reading streamed immediately. The stats panel below is
      held back by a deliberately slow server-side query
      (<code><%= @delay_ms %>ms</code> &mdash; change it with
      <code>?delay_ms=3000</code>), so its Suspense boundary resolves after the
      first HTML flush. Watch the skeleton get replaced by streamed HTML before
      any client JavaScript runs.
    </p>
  </header>

  <main class="surface">
    <%= stream_react_component_with_async_props("SlowSectionApp",
          props: { delayMs: @delay_ms }) do |emit|
      # Demo only: sleep stands in for a slow database query. It blocks this
      # Puma thread on purpose so the boundary reliably resolves post-shell.
      sleep(@delay_ms / 1000.0)
      emit.call("slowStats", {
        renderedAt: Time.current.utc.iso8601(3),
        delayMs: @delay_ms,
        totals: { open: 4, doing: 2, done: 7 }
      })
    end %>
  </main>
</div>
